Domestic reactions to the January 6 United States Capitol attack
added: On January 13, hours after [[Second impeachment of Donald Trump|his second impeachment]], Trump reiterated his condemnation of the violence in a video published by the White House. He did not claim responsibility for the riot. In the wake of the suspensions of his social media accounts, he denounced "the unprecedented assault on free speech we have seen in recent days", saying that "[w]hat is needed now is for us to listen to one another, not to silence one another."<ref>{{cite web |last1=Breuninger |first1=Kevin |title=Trump, facing second impeachment trial, condemns Capitol violence a week after riot |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2021/01/13/trump-condemns-capitol-violence-a-week-after-riot-as-he-faces-second-impeachment-trial.html |website=CNBC |publisher=CNBC |access-date=January 14, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210114043010/https://www.cnbc.com/2021/01/13/trump-condemns-capitol-violence-a-week-after-riot-as-he-faces-second-impeachment-trial.html |archive-date=January 14, 2021 |date=January 13, 2021 |url-status=live}}</ref>

title: Domestic reactions to the January 6 United States Capitol attack
added: In addition to the dozens of police officers who [[2021 storming of the United States Capitol#Participating groups|participated in the rally and storming of the Capitol]], many law enforcement officials made statements in support of the rally.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theappeal.org/the-cops-at-the-capitol/|title=The Cops at the Capitol|date=January 13, 2021|access-date=February 5, 2021|work=The Appeal|first=Jonathan|last=Ben-Menachem}}</ref> [[John Catanzara]], chair of the Chicago [[Fraternal Order of Police]], said that the rioters who attacked the Capitol were "entitled to voice their frustration" and claimed the event, which resulted in several deaths, had been non-violent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wbez.org/stories/chicago-police-union-president-defends-those-who-stormed-us-capitol/6842fa80-3b83-4396-af05-a5f15f4ac740|title=Chicago Police Union President Defends Those Who Stormed The U.S. Capitol|date=January 7, 2021|accessdate=February 5, 2021|publisher=[[WBEZ]]|first=Chip|last=Mitchell}}</ref>
